SIMPLE: round
RECORDS: 7

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Round
<hw>Round</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i. & t.</pos> <ety>[From
<er>Roun</er>.]</ety> <def>To whisper.</def> <mark>[obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Shak. Holland.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The Bishop of Glasgow <qex>rounding</qex> in his ear, ⟦ldquo⟧Ye
are not a wise man,⟦rdquo⟧ . . . he <qex>rounded</qex> likewise to the
bishop, and said, ⟦ldquo⟧Wherefore brought ye me here?⟦rdquo⟧</q>
<rj><qau>Calderwood.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Round</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Round
<hw>Round</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[OF. <ets>roond</ets>,
<ets>roont</ets>, <ets>reond</ets>, F. <ets>rond</ets>, fr. L.
<ets>rotundus</ets>, fr. <ets>rota</ets> wheel. See <er>Rotary</er>, and
cf. <er>Rotund</er>, <er>roundel</er>, <er>Rundlet</er>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>Having every portion of the surface or of the
circumference equally distant from the center; spherical; circular;
having a form approaching a spherical or a circular shape; orbicular;
globular; <as>as, a <ex>round</ex> ball</as>.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧The big,
<xex>round</xex> tears.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Upon the firm opacous globe⟦br⟧
Of this <qex>round</qex> world.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Having the form of a cylinder; cylindrical; <as>as,
the barrel of a musket is <ex>round</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Having a curved outline or form; especially, one
like the arc of a circle or an ellipse, or a portion of the surface of a
sphere; rotund; bulging; protuberant; not angular or pointed; <as>as, a
<ex>round</ex> arch; <ex>round</ex> hills.</as></def> ⟦ldquo⟧Their
<xex>round</xex> haunches gored.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Full; complete; not broken; not fractional;
approximately in even units, tens, hundreds, thousands, etc.; -- said of
numbers.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Pliny put a <qex>round</qex> number near the truth, rather than
the fraction.</q> <rj><qau>Arbuthnot.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>Not inconsiderable; large; hence, generous; free;
<as>as, a <ex>round</ex> price</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Three thousand ducats; 'tis a good <qex>round</qex> sum.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Round</qex> was their pace at first, but slackened soon.</q>
<rj><qau>Tennyson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>Uttered or emitted with a full tone; <as>as, a
<ex>round</ex> voice; a <ex>round</ex> note.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <fld>(Phonetics)</fld> <def>Modified, as a vowel, by
contraction of the lip opening, making the opening more or less round in
shape; rounded; labialized; labial. See <xex>Guide to
Pronunciation</xex>, ⟦sect⟧ 11.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>8.</sn> <def>Outspoken; plain and direct; unreserved;
unqualified; not mincing; <as>as, a <ex>round</ex> answer; a
<ex>round</ex> oath.</as></def> ⟦ldquo⟧The <xex>round</xex>
assertion.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>M. Arnold.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Sir Toby, I must be <qex>round</qex> with you.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>9.</sn> <def>Full and smoothly expanded; not defective or abrupt;
finished; polished; -- said of style, or of authors with reference to
their style.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>In his satires Horace is quick, <qex>round</qex>, and
pleasant.</q> <rj><qau>Peacham.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>10.</sn> <def>Complete and consistent; fair; just; -- applied to
conduct.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Round</qex> dealing is the honor of man's nature.</q>
<rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>At a round rate</b></col>, <cd>rapidly.</cd>
<au>Dryden.</au> -- <col><b>In round numbers</b></col>,
<cd>approximately in even units, tens, hundreds, etc.; <as>as, a bin
holding 99 or 101 bushels may be said to hold <ex>in round numbers</ex>
100 bushels</as>.</cd> -- <col><b>Round bodies</b></col>
<fld>(Geom.)</fld>, <cd>the sphere right cone, and right cylinder.</cd>
-- <col><b>Round clam</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>the quahog.</cd>
-- <col><b>Round dance</b></col> <cd>one which is danced by couples with
a whirling or revolving motion, as the waltz, polka, etc.</cd> --
<col><b>Round game</b></col>, <cd>a game, as of cards, in which each
plays on his own account.</cd> -- <col><b>Round hand</b></col>, <cd>a
style of penmanship in which the letters are formed in nearly an upright
position, and each separately distinct; -- distinguished from
<xex>running hand</xex>.</cd> -- <col><b>Round robin</b></col>.
<ety>[Perhaps F. <ets>round</ets> round + <ets>ruban</ets>
ribbon.]</ety> <sd>(a)</sd> <cd>A written petition, memorial,
remonstrance, protest, etc., the signatures to which are made in a
circle so as not to indicate who signed first.</cd> ⟦ldquo⟧No <xex>round
robins</xex> signed by the whole main deck of the Academy or the
Porch.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>De Quincey.</au> <sd>(b)</sd> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>
<cd>The cigar fish.</cd> -- <col><b>Round shot</b></col>, <cd>a solid
spherical projectile for ordnance.</cd> -- <col><b>Round
Table</b></col>, <cd>the table about which sat King Arthur and his
knights. See <cref>Knights of the Round Table</cref>, under
<er>Knight</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Round tower</b></col>, <cd>one of
certain lofty circular stone towers, tapering from the base upward, and
usually having a conical cap or roof, which crowns the summit, -- found
chiefly in Ireland. They are of great antiquity, and vary in heigh from
thirty-five to one hundred and thiry feet.</cd> -- <col><b>Round
trot</b></col>, <cd>one in which the horse throws out his feet roundly;
a full, brisk, quick trot.</cd> <au>Addison.</au> -- <col><b>Round
turn</b></col> <fld>(Naut.)</fld>, <cd>one turn of a rope round a
timber, a belaying pin, etc.</cd> -- <col><b>To bring up with a round
turn</b></col>, <cd>to stop abruptly.</cd>
<mark>[Colloq.]</mark></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Circular; spherical; globular; globase;
orbicular; orbed; cylindrical; full; plump; rotund.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Round</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Round
<hw>Round</hw> <pr>(round)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Anything
round, as a circle, a globe, a ring. ⟦ldquo⟧The golden
<xex>round</xex>⟦rdquo⟧ [the crown].</def> <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>In labyrinth of many a <qex>round</qex> self-rolled.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A series of changes or events ending where it began;
a series of like events recurring in continuance; a cycle; a periodical
revolution; <as>as, the <ex>round</ex> of the seasons; a <ex>round</ex>
of pleasures.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <specif>Hence:</specif> <def>A course ending where it
began; a circuit; a beat; especially, one freguently or regulary
traversed; also, the act of traversing a circuit; <as>as, a watchman's
<ex>round</ex>; the <ex>rounds</ex> of the postman</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A series of duties or tasks which must be performed
in turn, and then repeated.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>the trivial <qex>round</qex>, the common task.</q>
<rj><qau>Keble.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <specif>Hence:</specif> <fld>(Mining, Tunneling)</fld>
<def>One work cycle, consisting of drilling blast holes, loading them
with explosive, blasting, mucking out, and, if necessary, installing
temporary support.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>RH</source>]</p>

<p><q> . . . <company>Inco</company> is still much more advanced than
other mining companies. He says that the LKAB mine in
<country>Sweden</country> is the closest rival. He predicts that, by
2008, <company>Inco</company> can reach a new productivity plateau,
doubling the current mining productivity from 3,350 tonnes to 6,350
tonnes per person per year. Another aim is to triple the mine cycle rate
(the time to drill, blast and muck a <qex>round</qex>) from one cycle to
three complete cycles per 24 hours.</q>
<qau>https://web.archive.org/web/20010728040054/http://www.canadianminingjournal.com/issues/apr00/page10.asp</qau>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>A course of action or conduct performed by a number
of persons in turn, or one after another, as if seated in a
circle.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Women to cards may be compared: we play⟦br⟧
A <qex>round</qex> or two; which used, we throw away.</q>
<rj><qau>Granville.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The feast was served; the bowl was crowned;⟦br⟧
To the king's pleasure went the mirthful <qex>round</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Prior.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <specif>Hence:</specif> <def>A complete set of plays in a
game or contest covering a standard number of individual plays or parts;
<as>as, a <ex>round</ex> of golf; a <ex>round</ex> of
tennis</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>8.</sn> <specif>Hence:</specif> <def>One set of games in a
tournament.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>9.</sn> <def>The time during which prize fighters or boxers are
in actual contest without an intermission, as prescribed by their rules;
a bout.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>10.</sn> <def>A circular dance.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Come, knit hands, and beat the ground,⟦br⟧
In a light fantastic <qex>round</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>11.</sn> <def>That which goes round a whole circle or company;
<as>as, a <ex>round</ex> of applause</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>12.</sn> <def>Rotation, as in office; succession.</def>
<rj><au>Holyday.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>13.</sn> <def>The step of a ladder; a rundle or rung; also, a
crosspiece which joins and braces the legs of a chair.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>All the <qex>rounds</qex> like Jacob's ladder rise.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>14.</sn> <fld>(Mil.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>A walk performed by
a guard or an officer round the rampart of a garrison, or among
sentinels, to see that the sentinels are faithful and all things safe;
also, the guard or officer, with his attendants, who performs this duty;
-- usually in the plural.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>A general discharge of
firearms by a body of troops in which each soldier fires once.</def>
<sd>(c)</sd> <def>One piece of ammunition for a firearm, used by
discharging one piece at a time; <as>as, each soldier carried a hundred
<ex>rounds</ex> of ammunition</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>15.</sn> <fld>(Mus.)</fld> <def>A short vocal piece, resembling a
catch in which three or four voices follow each other round in a species
of canon in the unison.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>16.</sn> <def>A brewer's vessel in which the fermentation is
concluded, the yeast escaping through the bunghole.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>17.</sn> <def>A vessel filled, as for drinking; <as>as, to drink
a <ex>round</ex> od ale together</as>.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>18.</sn> <def>An assembly; a group; a circle; <as>as, a
<ex>round</ex> of politicians</as>.</def> <rj><au>Addison.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>19.</sn> <fld>(Naut.)</fld> <def>See <er>Roundtop</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>20.</sn> <def>Same as <cref>Round of beef</cref>,
below.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<cs><p><col><b>Gentlemen of the round</b></col>. <sd>(a)</sd>
<cd>Gentlemen soldiers of low rank who made the rounds. See 10
<sd>(a)</sd>, above.</cd> <sd>(b)</sd> <cd>Disbanded soldiers who lived
by begging.</cd> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Worm-eaten <qex>gentlemen of the round</qex>, such as have vowed
to sit on the skirts of the city, let your provost and his half dozen of
halberdiers do what they can.</q> <rj><qau>B. Jonson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p>-- <col><b>Round of beef</b></col>, <cd>the part of the thigh below
the aitchbone, or between the rump and the leg.</cd> See
<xex>Illust.</xex> of <er>beef</er>. -- <col><b>Round steak</b></col>,
<cd>a beefsteak cut from the round.</cd> -- <col><b>Sculpture in the
round</b></col>, <cd>sculpture giving the full form, as of man;
statuary, distinguished from relief.</cd>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p></cs>

<p><-- p. 1255 --></p>

<p><ent>Round</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Round
<hw>Round</hw>, <pos>adv.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>On all sides;
around.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Round</qex> he throws his baleful eyes.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Circularly; in a circular form or manner; by
revolving or reversing one's position; <as>as, to turn one's head
<ex>round</ex>; a wheel turns <ex>round</ex>.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>In circumference; <as>as, a ball is ten inches
<ex>round</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>From one side or party to another; as to come or
turn <xex>round</xex>, -- that is, to change sides or
opinions.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>By or in a circuit; by a course longer than the
direct course; back to the starting point.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>Through a circle, as of friends or houses.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The invitations were sent <qex>round</qex> accordingly.</q>
<rj><qau>Sir W. Scott.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <def>Roundly; fully; vigorously.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>All round</b></col>, <cd>over the whole place; in every
direction.</cd> -- <col><b>All-round</b></col>, <cd>of general capacity;
<as>as, an <ex>all-round</ex> man</as>.</cd> <mark>[Colloq.]</mark> --
<col><b>To bring one round</b></col>. <sd>(a)</sd> <cd>To cause one to
change his opinions or line of conduct</cd>. <sd>(b)</sd> <cd>To restore
one to health</cd>. <mark>[Colloq.]</mark></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Round</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 5 ====
HEADWORD: Round
<hw>Round</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>prep.</pos> <def>On every side of, so
as to encompass or encircle; around; about; <as>as, the people atood
<ex>round</ex> him; to go <ex>round</ex> the city; to wind a cable
<ex>round</ex> a windlass</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The serpent Error twines <qex>round</qex> human hearts.</q>
<rj><qau>Cowper.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Round about</b></col>, <cd>an emphatic form for
<xex>round</xex> or <xex>about</xex>.</cd> ⟦ldquo⟧Moses . . . set them
[The elders] <xex>round about</xex> the tabernacle.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Num. xi.
24.</au> -- <col><b>To come round</b></col>, <cd>to gain the consent of,
or circumvent, (a person) by flattery or deception.</cd>
<mark>[Colloq.]</mark></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Round</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 6 ====
HEADWORD: Round
<hw>Round</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Rounded</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Rounding</conjf>.]</vmorph> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To make circular,
spherical, or cylindrical; to give a round or convex figure to; <as>as,
to <ex>round</ex> a silver coin; to <ex>round</ex> the edges of
anything</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Worms with many feet, which <qex>round</qex> themselves into
balls, are bred chiefly under logs of timber.</q>
<rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The figures on our modern medals are raised and <qex>rounded</qex>
to a very great perfection.</q> <rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To surround; to encircle; to encompass.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The inclusive verge⟦br⟧
Of golden metal that must <qex>round</qex> my brow.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To bring to fullness or completeness; to complete;
hence, to bring to a fit conclusion.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>We are such stuff⟦br⟧
As dreams are made on, and our little life⟦br⟧
Is <qex>rounded</qex> with a sleep.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To go round wholly or in part; to go about (a corner
or point); <as>as, to <ex>round</ex> a corner; to <ex>round</ex> Cape
Horn</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To make full, smooth, and flowing; <as>as, to
<ex>round</ex> periods in writing</as>.</def>
<rj><au>Swift.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To round in</b></col> <fld>(Naut.)</fld> <cd>To haul up;
usually, to haul the slack of (a rope) through its leading block, or to
haul up (a tackle which hangs loose) by its fall.</cd> <au>Totten.</au>
<sd>(b)</sd> <cd>To collect together (cattle) by riding around them, as
on cattle ranches<-- round up --></cd>. <mark>[Western
U.S.]</mark></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Round</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 7 ====
HEADWORD: Round
<hw>Round</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To grow round or full;
hence, to attain to fullness, completeness, or perfection.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The queen your mother <qex>rounds</qex> apace.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>So <qex>rounds</qex> he to a separate mind,⟦br⟧
From whence clear memory may begin.</q>
<rj><qau>Tennyson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To go round, as a guard.</def>
<mark>[Poetic]</mark><-- = make the rounds -->⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They . . . nightly <qex>rounding</qex> walk.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To go or turn round; to wheel about.</def>
<rj><au>Tennyson.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To round to</b></col> <fld>(Naut.)</fld>, <cd>to turn the
head of a ship toward the wind.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Roundabout</ent>⟦br⟧
